      "term": "TN-S System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing system where the neutral and earth conductors are kept separate throughout the entire network from the transformer to the installation.",
      "anchor": "Separate all the way back to the source.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the earth and neutral are joined at the consumer's cut-out; in TN-S, they remain distinct."
    },
    {
      "term": "TN-C-S System",
      "simpleDefinition": "A system where the neutral and earth are combined in the supply cable but separated into two distinct conductors at the consumer's intake.",
      "anchor": "Combined in the street, separate in the house.",
      "misconception": "Believing the earth is separate for the whole journey; it is actually shared with the neutral in the supplier's cable."
    },
    {
      "term": "TT System",
      "simpleDefinition": "A system where the supplier does not provide an earth; the consumer must provide their own connection to the ground via an electrode.",
      "anchor": "Earth through the soil.",
      "misconception": "Assuming the supplier always provides an earth terminal for every property."
    },
    {
      "term": "ADS",
      "simpleDefinition": "Automatic Disconnection of Supply; a safety strategy that uses protective devices to cut power instantly during a fault.",
      "anchor": "Cut the power fast.",
      "misconception": "Thinking ADS is a single part; it is actually a system of conductors and devices working together."
    },
    {
      "term": "Circuit Protective Conductor (CPC)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The specific wire in a circuit that connects metal parts of equipment to the main earthing terminal.",
      "anchor": "The circuit's own earth wire.",
      "misconception": "Using the generic term 'earth wire' for everything; the CPC is specifically for the circuit it serves."
    },
    {
      "term": "Earthing Conductor",
      "simpleDefinition": "The main conductor that connects the installation's main earth terminal to the supplier's earth or an earth electrode.",
      "anchor": "The main link to the ground.",
      "misconception": "Confusing this with a CPC; the earthing conductor is the single main link for the whole building."
    },
    {
      "term": "Main Protective Bonding",
      "simpleDefinition": "Conductors used to connect metal services like gas and water pipes to the main earthing terminal.",
      "anchor": "Connecting the pipes to earth.",
      "misconception": "Thinking bonding is meant to carry fault current from a faulty appliance; its job is to keep all metalwork at the same voltage."
    },
    {
      "term": "Earth Electrode",
      "simpleDefinition": "A metal rod or plate driven into the ground to provide a physical connection to the earth, primarily used in TT systems.",
      "anchor": "The rod in the ground.",
      "misconception": "Believing every installation requires a rod; they are usually only required when the supplier doesn't provide an earth."
    },
    {
      "term": "Protective Device",
      "simpleDefinition": "A component such as a circuit breaker (MCB), fuse, or RCD that automatically breaks the circuit during a fault.",
      "anchor": "The switch that trips.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the earth wire itself stops the electricity; the earth wire only provides the path that allows the device to trip."
    }
  ],
